## What's this article about?

As engineers, we are used to treating our CRUD operations straightforwardly. We receive requests that we process and modify or create data in our databases, ready to be fetched when a request to retrieve the data is received.

In high-availability read-heavy systems, we are always trying to improve the performance of read operations. The most common way to achieve this is by the usage of a **Caching Strategy**.

There are 4 common strategies that can be used in order to achieve an improvement in performance:

**Cache-aside:** The cache sits on the side and the application directly talks to both the cache and the database.

**Read-through:** When there is a cache miss, it loads missing data from the database, populates the cache, and returns it to the application.

**Write-through:** The cache sits in-line with the database and writes always go through the cache to the main database.

**Write-back or Write-behind:** The application writes data to the cache which stores the data and acknowledges the change immediately. Later, the cache writes the data back to the database.

The main issue with read-heavy systems and the usage of caching, is when the data on the database changes, how do we keep track of those changes? Do we keep using the stale data for some time until it expires using TTL (Time-To-Live) values?

The same happens with write-heavy services which are constantly receiving requests to update values stored. Modifying the stored information is less performant than a reading request. Normally, it involves data transformation, triggering some other events, validation of the data, etc. All of those add to the latency of the overall request.

The purpose of this article is to dive into a possible solution to these issues by implementing a Write-back (also known as Write-behind), combined with Read-through cache, working with a remote Redis cluster, in order to improve performance on the CRUD operations. We will then asynchronously generate queue events to update the database. The solution should act as a database accelerator that will speed up your operations and allow you to handle more requests.

## What are we trying to implement?

Let's say that we need to implement a service that holds a score for an item. The score will be updated constantly and we need to provide the most up-to-date value for it every time we receive a request to read the item's value.

The whole process needs to happen with the lowest latency possible due to the write-heavy and read-heavy nature of the system. For this, we'll leverage the caching techniques mentioned above.

Our solution will be composed of a service acting as an API, which receives requests and communicates with our Redis cluster, which stores the items with their score. Another service will act as a Worker, receiving jobs from the queue on Redis to which it subscribes. The Redis clusters for the data and the queue could be the same, depending on the capacity of the cluster you are willing to deploy.

### Updating a score

Writing data is divided into two processes. The first is the interaction that we perform with Redis, and the second is the event we raise with the queue so the database can be updated.

The sequence of operations is:

1. We receive a request to modify an item's value.
2. We perform any transformations or validations of the received data.
3. If we don't have the item's current data on Redis, we perform a read from the database and populate the data on Redis.
4. We proceed to update the data on Redis according to the received request.
5. Generate a new job request for the Queue hosted on Redis, so the Worker service can pick it up and update the database.

In step number three, when we populate Redis with the missing data, we should be cautious of how long we want the data's TTL to be. *A small value would cause us to query the database too often, but a large value would cause our Redis cluster memory usage to be high.*

When creating the job request to submit to Redis, the idea is not to submit one job per request we receive. That will make the worker service deal with many requests as it tries to reflect in the database all the values that the item(s) were assigned. Instead, we should *send our job to the queue with an identifier that references the item being updated.* This way, when a new write request gets received and the step to send the job to Redis is reached, we can check if there is already an existing job in the queue associated with the item which has not been processed yet. Then, the value in the job that has not been processed can be updated and the worker service will not have to unnecessarily process jobs that do not represent the most recent value submitted.

### Returning a Score

Our read process will be similar to a Read-through caching strategy.

1. We receive a request to read and return the value of an item.
2. We try to obtain the requested value from the Redis cluster holding our data.
3. If the data is missing, we fetch it from the database.
4. The data is populated in the Redis cache before being returned.
5. The data is sent back as a response.

In step number three, we need to keep in mind the same TTL concerns as in the writing process.

Populating the data on Redis will help us perform any upcoming operation (whether read or write) as fast as possible and without having to query the database.

### Processing the Queue

Processing the queue of jobs stored on Redis will be performed by the worker instance of our service. This worker, will subscribe to the queue and trigger the update process on the database once a job is assigned to the worker for processing.

When a job is picked, we don't simply go ahead and update the value we received from the job for the item on the database, because there is a chance that our data stored in the database was updated by another process, or manually by an engineer, more recently than the data we received from the job.

At this point, we need to introduce a *data version*.

Each of our items stored on the database should have a property/field holding the *DateTime* when it was most recently updated. This way, we can check which "version" of the data is the most recent. We should also make sure that the job we submit to our queue has the DateTime from when it was set on the Redis cluster for data.

During job processing, we can check which of the two pieces of data related to the item is most current, and use it to store in the database (or keep it in case it holds the most recent data) or to update Redis.

This way, we can guarantee that our up-to-date data is propagated in our system.

### Data for Items Stored in Redis and their TTL

As mentioned in the *Updating a Score* section, one important thing to consider is how much TTL (Time-To-Live) we assign to the data stored in Redis. Check the section again to clear any doubts about the selection of TTL for your data entries.

One suggestion is, to analyze the system where you would like to implement this async accelerator to see how often the data gets updated when there is a spike in requests. If there is a scenario in which you believe data will be requested a lot and very often, how long do you believe the spike in requests will last?

Assuming that your eviction policy on the Redis cluster for your data is *least-recently-used* (LRU), you will know that the TTL which was chosen is having the intended effect if the data that remains in the Redis cluster is not changing the memory usage too abruptly or reaching limits too often. Also, the entries stored in it are referenced often and without having to refresh them from the database very frequently.

## Things to Keep in Mind about Asynchronous Processing

There are some things to keep in mind when we are dealing with an asynchronous way to update our data and handle it using workers.

For example, what do you do if one of your Redis servers is down? Do you return a Service Unavailable exception if one of your dependencies is unavailable? What to do when updating an entry on the database fails? What if your data in Redis is up-to-date but the database cannot keep up and is lagging significantly?

There are many questions and the right answers depend on the characteristics of the implementation of the system that you are trying to build and its dependencies.

Here are some possible considerations.

If either of your Redis clusters (for the data or for the jobs queue), or the database is inaccessible, you should not accept any more requests to be processed. This way, the queue won't get clogged with jobs that cannot be processed, and the database will stay as up-to-date as possible.

If the job queue's size keeps increasing and the worker service is taking too much time to process them; try to increase the number of worker instances running. Another thing you can do is check if indexes can improve the speed at which the database processes requests. One more step could be increasing the resources assigned to the database. A database cluster is what's recommended, this way you can have a main instance of the database serving the writes, and two or more secondary instances serving the read operations.

Let's say that a job to change the value of an item fails.

One possible solution could be failing the job altogether and removing the entry from the Redis cluster with the data. The next time a request asks for the item, it will get populated once again, and your cache and database will be in sync. However, that violates the initial principle of our solution which is not just to be performant but also reliable.

Another possibility is to send the job to a retry queue which will try to process the failing job until it succeeds or a new job for the same item gets queued. If another job for the same item gets queued we can remove the failing job from the retry queue, because the new job has the most recent value we should have for the item.

One final possibility is to fail the request if the new value for an item has a job that is in a failed status, or in the retry queue. This solution is more suitable for systems that need absolute accuracy on the stored value when processing a request.

## What was used to implement the solution?

A proof-of-concept application was built using NodeJS, NestJS, TypeScript, Redis, BullJS, and MongoDB were used in order to implement the solution we talked about in this article.

There is a repository with a service implemented that you can run locally using Docker Compose to see the accelerator in action.

You can run a Python script stored on the repository, that executes different threads submitting requests to the running service and validates that the service is properly returning the expected value every time it is requested. At the end of the test, a summary of how many times the service failed to return the right values is printed.

